  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What pre-action would you take in case of earthquakes?",
  "response": "Taking pre-action steps before an earthquake can significantly reduce the risk of injury, property damage, and other hazards. Here are key measures to prepare:\n\n### 1. **Emergency Plan**\n   - Develop a family or workplace emergency plan, including evacuation routes and meeting points.\n   - Assign roles (e.g., who turns off utilities, who grabs emergency supplies).\n   - Practice earthquake drills regularly.\n\n### 2. **Emergency Kit**\n   - Prepare a disaster supply kit with essentials:\n     - Water (1 gallon per person per day for at least 3 days).\n     - Non-perishable food (3-day supply).\n     - First aid kit, medications, and hygiene items.\n     - Flashlight, batteries, portable radio, and multi-tool.\n     - Cash, copies of important documents, and emergency contacts.\n     - Blankets, extra clothing, and sturdy shoes.\n\n### 3. **Secure Your Space**\n   - Anchor heavy furniture, appliances, and electronics to walls.\n   - Install safety latches on cabinets to prevent items from falling.\n   - Secure overhead light fixtures and ceiling fans.\n   - Store heavy or breakable items on lower shelves.\n\n### 4. **Know Your Environment**\n   - Identify safe spots in each room (e.g., under sturdy tables, against interior walls).\n   - Stay away from windows, mirrors, and heavy objects that could fall.\n\n### 5. **Preparing Your Home**\n   - Reinforce your home\u2019s structure if necessary (e.g., bolting the foundation, adding braces).\n   - Install flexible gas and water lines to reduce rupture risk.\n   - Learn how to shut off utilities (gas, water, electricity).\n\n### 6. **Stay Informed**\n   - Sign up for local emergency alerts and weather notifications.\n   - Know the earthquake risks in your area and stay updated on preparedness tips.\n\n### 7. **Educate Yourself**\n   - Learn basic first aid and CPR.\n   - Understand the \u201cDrop, Cover, and Hold On\u201d technique for during an earthquake.\n\nBy taking these pre-action steps, you can minimize risks and ensure a safer response during and after an earthquake.",
